Klassic Kinks: Revisiting Those Early "K" Albums

Your typical Kinks fan of the '70s and '80s did not own a stack of their albums and only one or two of their 1960s LPs scaled the upper reaches of the Billboard album chart. Author Daniel de Vis focuses on some of the highlights of their American catalog.

New Releases

This week Spanish singer Rosala juxtaposes the experimental and tender, Sonic Youth collects a series of late-era instrumentals, and Broadcast release three albums of previously hard-to-find odds and ends.

Interview

These Things Happen: The Enduring Magic of Sarah Records

Sarah Records alumni Amelia Fletcher and Rob Pursey (of Heavenly) talk about the legacy of the influential indie pop label as celebrated on the new Under the Bridge collection they've just released on their Skep Wax label.

A Rundown of the 2022 Oscar Nominations for Best Original Song

While the Oscars are still a few weeks away, it's never too early to explore the songs nominated for film's most distinguished prize. Each brings something unique to the table, and here's a rundown of the five nominees for Best Original Song.

Editors' Choice

Each month the AllMusic editors highlight the albums they found to be most worth listening to. In February, British duo Binker & Moses wove an intoxicating, fully improvised meld of sounds, textures, and grooves, Cate Le Bon replaced detail-oriented songcraft with smears of dense synth pop and plastic funk, and Avril Lavigne (pictured) reclaimed her pop-punk crown.

Interview

Cloud Cult's Craig Minowa Navigates Self-Transformation in the Midst of Upheaval on Metamorphosis

In an interview with AllMusic, Cloud Cult's Craig Minowa discusses the inspirations for their single "One Way Out of a Hole," the development of their upcoming album Metamorphosis, and the medicinal power he hopes it evokes for listeners.

AllMusic Staff Picks

More Staff Picks

Duke Ellington

Anatomy of a Murder [Original Motion Picture Soundtrack]

1959

Big Band

With its rich and varied emotional moods and existential outcome, the full range of the composer's previous work was brought to bear on this 1959 work -- tension and release, danger and safety, movement and stillness, darkness and light; the textural palette that was Ellington's signature was always compellingly cinematic. In these orchestral settings, his soloists (Cat Anderson, Clark Terry, Johnny Hodges, and others) shine, as their playing reflects true variations on a theme in a classical sense. That's not to say that this set doesn't swing, too -- "Happy Anatomy" is a short but fully cranked gallop.

- TiVo Staff

Nigo

Ape Sounds

November 21, 1999

Electronica

Nigo's first album is a relic of the era when Grand Royal and Mo Wax were the hippest labels around, and SPIN magazine was one of the most relevant voices in alternative culture. The album was internationally released on James Lavelle's imprint in 2000, and it features contributions from Cornelius, Ben Lee, Money Mark, and many others. It's all over the place, hopscotching from Japanese hip-hop to dub to mellow psych-pop to noisy punk, but the detached trip-hop splendor of "Too Much" is the best and most haunting cut overall.

- Paul Simpson
